# Container Launch Fixes

This walkthrough details the structural fixes made to Winlator's container generation, game execution flow, and architecture support.

## Issue 1: Game Settings Creating Redundant Containers

**The Bug**: Whenever a user clicked "Game Settings" on a game and saved, [ContainerDetailFragment.java](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/ContainerDetailFragment.java) would unconditionally call `manager.createContainerAsync()` without attaching a Shortcut. This resulted in phantom containers proliferating in the system.

**The Fix**:
```diff
-  // Create new container with specified properties
-  JSONObject data = new JSONObject();
-  data.put("name", name);
+ // Try to find an existing container with the matching Wine version
+ Container targetContainer = null;
+ for (Container c : manager.getContainers()) {
+     if (c.getWineVersion().equals(finalWineVersion)) {
+         targetContainer = c;
+         break;
+     }
+ }
```
If an existing container is found that matches the user's selected Wine version, we now generate a `.desktop` Shortcut on that existing container using our new [createShortcutOnContainer()](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/ContainerDetailFragment.java#1352-1379) helper method, appending the settings as `[Extra Data]`. A new container is only created if a compatible one doesn't exist yet.

## Issue 2: Games Failing to Auto-Launch

**The Bug**: When you launched a game directly from the Library without any Game Settings configured, [UnifiedActivity.kt](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/UnifiedActivity.kt) attempted to inject an ephemeral `executablePath` variable to the container. However, [XServerDisplayActivity](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/XServerDisplayActivity.java#137-2018) logic completely ignores the container's `executablePath` execution string unless an actual `.desktop` shortcut path is supplied. Because no shortcut was passed, the activity fell back to `wfm.exe`.

**The Fix**:
Instead of relying on `container.executablePath`, [UnifiedActivity.kt](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/UnifiedActivity.kt) now dynamically generates a clean `.desktop` shortcut file targeting the found EXE.
```kotlin
// Generate a shortcut dynamically
val desktopDir = container.getDesktopDir()
if (!desktopDir.exists()) desktopDir.mkdirs()
val shortcutFile = java.io.File(desktopDir, "${app.name.replace("/", "_")}.desktop")
val content = java.lang.StringBuilder()
content.append("[Desktop Entry]\n")
content.append("Type=Application\n")
content.append("Name=${app.name}\n")
content.append("Exec=$execPath\n")
...
```
This forces [XServerDisplayActivity](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/XServerDisplayActivity.java#137-2018) to execute the game's executable path successfully upon boot.

## Issue 3: x86_64 Containers Failing to Boot

**The Bug**: Box64 environments in [GuestProgramLauncherComponent.java](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/xenvironment/components/GuestProgramLauncherComponent.java) restricted their `HODLL` override environment variables exclusively to [isArm64EC()](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/core/WineInfo.java#71-72) containers. Pure `x86_64` containers lacked these variables entirely. Without `wowbox64.dll` or `libwow64fex.dll` hook configurations, attempting to run Wine natively inside Box64 resulted in a fail-to-boot cascade during 32-bit execution checks.

**The Fix**:
```diff
- if (wineInfo.isArm64EC()) {
-     command = winePath + "/" + guestExecutable;
-     if (emulator.toLowerCase().equals("fexcore"))
-         envVars.put("HODLL", "libwow64fex.dll");
-     else
-         envVars.put("HODLL", "wowbox64.dll");
- }

+ if (emulator.toLowerCase().equals("fexcore"))
+     envVars.put("HODLL", "libwow64fex.dll");
+ else
+     envVars.put("HODLL", "wowbox64.dll");
```
By lifting the `HODLL` condition out of the [isArm64EC()](file:///home/max/Build/Emulator/WinNative/app/src/main/java/com/winlator/cmod/core/WineInfo.java#71-72) block, `x86_64` containers are now natively supplied with the necessary WoW64 emulation intercept configurations.
